 section.\r\n </div><div><b>8.7 Content Moderation, Notices and Appeals\r\n </b></div><div>·         Owrners is usually not bound to monitor the content uploaded by the users, as to its legal standards or compliance with Terms. We are nonetheless entitled to perform random checks on our own initiative in order to identify and define what is illegal or incompatible content and to take the necessary actions. We may respond if we discover, or are informed of, a breach to the Terms. For more details about our content moderation policy, please go here.\r\n </div><div>·         In case Owrners takes action with regard to you, your account or content, you can appeal against this action. You may also file a complaint if you are dissatisfied with the decision that we make when you have made a notice to us. In both cases the time for filing a complaint is within six months from the notification of the above said decision to you. You can therefore file a complaint by reporting to our Customer Support. Kindly state in your complaint why you think that we should reverse the decision in your favor.\r\n </div><div>·         It will respond to complaints in a timely and non-discriminatory manner and will exercise due diligence in handling the complaint while being impartial and will change its decision if it is convinced that the decision to have been taken in error.\r\n </div><div>We reserve the right to refuse to cooperate with the selected Dispute Settlement Body if; (i) the respective dispute has already been resolved or is already pending before the competent court or before another competent Dispute Settlement Body; or (ii) the six months period from the notification of our decision to you has elapsed without you filing a complaint through internal complaint-handling or to the Dispute Settlement Body.\r\n </div><div>Dispute Settlement Bodies’ decisions do not become final and are non-enforceable against the parties.\r\n </div><div><b>8.8 Proprietary Restrictions\r\n </b></div